3 Reading in the rdata file (List from last lesson)
In previous lesson, we opened up a CSV file and saved the data to a data frame using read.csv().Â  In this lesson, we are going to use some of the data frames created in the last lesson â€“ data frames that were saved to a rdata file in the data folder of our project.
Â 
From last lesson:
# save(temperatureDFs, file = "data/tempDFs.rdata");
Now, letâ€™s open up the file using load():
load(file = "data/tempDFs.rdata");
Inside the rdata file is a List object, temperatureDFs,Â  with four data frames.Â  In the next couple lessons we will be dealing a lot more with navigating and creating List objects.Â  For now, a List object is a container for other object (like data frames). load() takes the objects from the rdata file and puts in the Environment:






FigureÂ 1: The List object from the rdata file â€“ it is a carbon copy of the List object from last lesson




3.1 Extracting the data frames
The data frames inside the List can be extracted just like a column can be extracted from a data frame.Â  Letâ€™s extract the four data frame using the ( $ ) subset operator:
lansJanTempsDF = temperatureDFs$origDF;
stackedDF = temperatureDFs$stackedDF;
stackedDF2 = temperatureDFs$stackDF_3_6;
stackedDF3 = temperatureDFs$stackedDF_1_2_5_6;
This put the data frames directly in the Environment:
â® lansJanTempsDF:   31 obs. of 6 variables
â® stackedDF:        186 obs. of 2 variables
