5.1 GGPlot components
In GGPlot, you initialize a canvas and then add components to the canvas.Â  The ( + ) symbol is used to add components, and you can string multiple components together.Â  In the above example, there is the canvas initialization function, ggplot(), and one component, geom_point():
Â 
1) ggplot() is used to initialize a GGPlot canvas with the data from weatherData:
plotData = Â«ggplot( data=weatherData )Â» +
           geom_point( mapping=aes(x=avgTemp, y=relHum) );
2) geom_point() is a plotting component that creates a scatterplot
plotData = ggplot( data=weatherData ) +
           Â«geom_point( mapping=aes(x=avgTemp, y=relHum) )Â»;


5.2 GGPlot mapping and aesthetics (aes)
Most plotting components in GGPlot contain a subcomponent called mapping.Â  mapping describes the relationship between the data and the plot.Â  Or, another way to put it, mapping describes what data gets represented on the plot (in the above case, avgTemp and relHum) and how the data gets represented (avgTemp on x-axis, relHum on y-axis):Â 
plotData = ggplot( data=weatherData ) +
           geom_point( mapping=Â«aes(x=avgTemp, y=relHum)Â» );
The mapping is set to a mapping element called an aesthetic (aes).Â  The concept of an aesthetic comes into play when we are generating legends and creating data categories, which is a topic we delve much deeper into in the GGPlot class.

